<DOC><DOCNO> AP891001-0071 </DOCNO><FILEID>AP-NR-10-01-89 2148EDT</FILEID><FIRST>r a AM-GangViolence     10-01 0195</FIRST><SECOND>AM-Gang Violence,0200</SECOND><HEAD>Weekend Anti-Gang Sweeps Net Thousand Arrests</HEAD><DATELINE>LOS ANGELES (AP) </DATELINE><TEXT>   A police task force trying to suppress gangviolence arrested more than 1,000 people during weekend sweeps ofgang territories in Los Angeles and San Fernando Valley,authorities said Sunday.   Hundreds of officers were deployed in both areas Friday nightand again Saturday night, watching for any offenses and checkingfor warrants.   Police made 472 arrests Friday night and 624 arrest Saturdaynight. Of the total, 345 were suspected gang members, police said.   Gang attacks continued despite the sweeps, the latest in along-running series of sweeps that Police Chief Daryl Gates callsOperation Hammer.   A 15-year-old boy, Nelson R. Alas, an alleged gang member, wasshot and killed early Sunday in Hollywood, said Detective BillHumphry. Alas and another youth were on a bicycle when they wereconfronted by a gang.   Words were exchanged before the unidentified gang members shotAlas to death, Humphry said. The other youth was not hurt.   A spate of drive-by shootings, a typical method of gang attack,killed one man and wounded seven people in greater Los Angelesbetween Friday evening and early Saturday morning.</TEXT></DOC>